55. An appeal to an otherwise unknown Camerius to disclose his whereabouts to his friend, who has been searching through Rome for him. Similar descriptions of an anx· ious search for a friend through the city are not wanting in the come· dians ; cf. Plaut. Amph. 1009 ff.; Epist 196 ff.; Ter. Ad. 713 ff. The poem appears to be an un· finished experiment in a not very pleasant modification of the Phalae- cean verse, and was perhaps, with the accompanying fragment, 58²³, found among the papers of Catullus after his death and published by the original editor of the Liber. The odd verses (and also v. 8) through v. 13, and from that point the even verses, have a spondee in the second place. In 58¹³, however, only vv. 1 and 9 have a spondee in the second place. —Date, 55 rac. (cf. v. 6 n.).
